---
// Figma file u4NLOVKuXUTKULhSn0sAJQ: eyebrow 1:9501, H1 lines 1:9505/1:9506/1:9507,
// lede 1:9508, curves+sparks group 1:9164. See exact derivations in style block below.
import HeroCurves from "../../assets/about/hero-curves.svg";
import ScrollArrow from "../../assets/about/scroll-arrow.svg";
import RevealStar from "../../assets/shared/reveal-star.svg";
---

<section class="hero">
  <div class="orbit" aria-hidden="true">
    <HeroCurves class="curves" />
  </div>

  <div class="hero-inner reveal">
    <p class="eyebrow">ABOUT</p>
    <div class="underline" aria-hidden="true"></div>

    <h1>
      <span class="line reveal-line">
        <span class="reveal-line-box">
          <span class="reveal-line-text">Where India&rsquo;s</span>
          <RevealStar class="reveal-star" aria-hidden="true" />
        </span>
      </span>
      <span class="line reveal-line">
        <span class="reveal-line-box">
          <span class="reveal-line-text accent">Energy Innovation</span>
          <RevealStar class="reveal-star" aria-hidden="true" />
        </span>
      </span>
      <span class="line reveal-line">
        <span class="reveal-line-box">
          <span class="reveal-line-text">gets built.</span>
          <RevealStar class="reveal-star" aria-hidden="true" />
        </span>
      </span>
    </h1>

    <p class="lede reveal-rise reveal-rise--after-3-lines">
      MC&sup2;+ exists with a single mandate: to catalyse Indian energy
      innovation and accelerate the country&rsquo;s energy security and
      transition.
    </p>

    <ScrollArrow class="scroll" aria-hidden="true" />
  </div>
</section>

<style>
  .hero {
    position: relative;
    overflow: hidden;
    background: var(--color-cream);
    /* Top spacing kept as-is (sits under the sticky header, not derived from
       Figma's absolute canvas). Bottom is zeroed so the Hero->Mission gap is
       owned entirely by Mission's own padding-block-start (see Mission.astro). */
    padding-block: 6rem 0;
  }
  /* No min-height on .hero (final-review fix, replaces the old
     `min-height: calc(960 * var(--fig))` floor this rule used to set — see
     the about-fix-report.md §4/§4a and initiatives' Hero.astro orbit-offset
     comment for the house precedent this follows). That floor was sized to
     the curve asset's own oval-bottom point (svg-local y=960,
     hero-curves.svg path "...960 960 C429.81 960 -0.000244141
     530.19...") so `.orbit`'s curve wouldn't clip — but this section's real
     text content (eyebrow→chevron) is only 601.40625px tall at 1920
     (measured via getBoundingClientRect), far short of 960px, so the floor
     left ~358.6px of dead space below the chevron before Mission began
     (Hero→Mission gap ~604.8px at 1920 vs the design's own 246.25px). Fix:
     shift the ART up instead of growing the BAND (see `.orbit`'s `top`
     override below) so the section's own content-driven auto height (no
     floor needed — same as <1024) already reveals the correct window of
     curve without clipping any spark or the oval. With no min-height,
     hero's box is exactly 601.40625px at 1920, so Mission's own
     padding-block-start (246.25px, unchanged) now IS the whole
     Hero→Mission gap — 0px delta from the design, down from +358.6px. The
     actual shift value lives in `.orbit`'s own >=1024px override, in a
     SEPARATE media block placed after `.orbit`'s base rule below — not
     merged into `.orbit`'s base rule itself, because `.orbit`'s base rule
     also sets `top`, and at equal specificity the LATER declaration in
     source order always wins regardless of which media query matches (see
     that block's own comment for the full reasoning — the same
     cascade-ordering rule the `.eyebrow`/`.underline`/`.lede` gate (further
     below, after their own base rules) follows for the same reason: an
     earlier revision of this file placed that gate BEFORE those three
     selectors' base rules, which made it dead code at every viewport — see
     about-fix-report.md §4a, fixed alongside this hero-band fix). */

  /* Curves + sparks: 1:9164 (fileKey u4NLOVKuXUTKULhSn0sAJQ) exports as a
     single 1920x1040 SVG (src/assets/about/hero-curves.svg) that already
     bakes in all 4 orange four-point sparks as filled paths (Vector_4-7)
     alongside the 3 stroked orbit curves (Vector/Vector_2/Vector_3) —
     confirmed via get_screenshot on 1:9164 and by inspecting the SVG's own
     path fills. Unlike the home hero (whose curves.svg holds only outline
     rings, requiring 3 separately-overlaid <SparkOrange> instances at
     guessed % positions), the About curves asset needs no overlay: dropping
     it in reproduces the design pixel-for-pixel with no manual positioning.
     spark-orange.svg exists in src/assets/about/ but is intentionally unused
     here for that reason. Base `top: 0` here is the original, untouched
     <1024 positioning (curve flush with .hero's own top edge); the
     >=1024px vertical-offset override (see media query below) is what the
     final-review hero-band fix shifts, so mobile keeps rendering exactly
     as it did before that fix. */
  .orbit {
    position: absolute;
    top: 0;
    left: 0;
    width: 100%;
    z-index: 0;
    pointer-events: none;
  }
  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    /* Deliberately a SEPARATE media block placed AFTER the base `.orbit`
       rule above — `.orbit`'s base rule also sets `top`, so this override
       has to win the cascade by SOURCE ORDER (equal specificity, later
       wins), not just by media-query truth. The `.eyebrow`/`.underline`/
       `.lede` gate further below (after `.hero-inner`) follows the same
       rule, placed after their own base rules for the same reason.

       Node 1:9164's own metadata reports the curve group at design-canvas
       y=79.87 while the hero copy group (node 1:9499, eyebrow→chevron)
       starts at design-canvas y=311.42 — i.e. in the design the curve's
       own top sits 231.55px ABOVE the copy, extending up behind where the
       shared site header renders (same "canvas y0 is BEHIND the header"
       situation initiatives/Hero.astro's own orbit-offset comment
       documents), not flush with the copy's own top the way the base
       `top: 0` above (.orbit flush with .hero's own top edge, right where
       .hero-inner's copy ALSO starts) renders it below 1024px. Re-deriving
       the exact shift from that design ratio still hits the same
       header-double-count problem initiatives did (About's live
       header-to-content spacing isn't Figma-derived at all — see the
       "kept as-is" .hero padding-top comment above), so this value is
       instead derived from the asset itself, empirically verified by
       rendering: hero-curves.svg's own path data (src/assets/about/
       hero-curves.svg) places the 4 sparks at svg-local y=[419.93,
       904.55] (Vector_6 top to Vector_7 bottom) and the oval's rounded
       bottom point at exactly y=960 (path "...960 960 C429.81 960
       -0.000244141 530.19..."). Shifting up by (960 − 601.40625) =
       358.59375px — 960 being that same oval-bottom, 601.40625px being
       the section's own real content height at 1920 (see the .hero
       min-height-removal comment above) — makes the section's now
       content-auto-height window land EXACTLY on [358.59375, 960] in the
       curve's local coordinates: comfortably below every spark's own top
       (419.93, 61.34px of margin) and comfortably above every spark's own
       bottom (904.55, 55.45px of margin), while its own lower edge lands
       exactly on the oval's rounded bottom (960) — zero clipping of the
       oval's curve (no "flat cut" edge), same as the old min-height:960
       version, clipping only the same faint Vector_3 tail past the oval
       it always clipped. Verified visually at 1920 (all 4 sparks + oval
       intact — see the report's evidence crops) and confirmed
       proportional at 1440 (both this shift and the removed min-height
       are --fig-scaled, so they move together with the rest of the
       section). Below 1024px, only the base rule above matches, so mobile
       keeps rendering exactly as it did before this fix. */
    .orbit {
      top: calc(-358.59375 * var(--fig));
    }
  }
  .curves {
    display: block;
    width: 100%;
    height: auto;
  }

  .hero-inner {
    position: relative;
    z-index: 1;
    max-width: 56rem; /* buffer above the 49.65rem lede width (1:9508) and 43.31rem widest H1 line (1:9506) */
    margin-inline: auto;
    padding-inline: 1.25rem;
    text-align: center;
  }

  .eyebrow {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: var(--text-hero-eyebrow); /* 27.07px, node 1:9501 — normalized to home hero scale per user directive 2026-07-06 */
    letter-spacing: 0.25em; /* 6.7675px / 27.07px = 0.25em exactly, node 1:9501 */
    color: var(--color-gray); /* #959595 exact match, node 1:9501 */
  }
  .underline {
    width: 11.77rem; /* 188.25px, node 1:9500 (hairline vector, height 0) */
    height: 1px;
    margin: 2.8rem auto 1.6rem; /* ~45.11px / ~26.15px gaps, nodes 1:9500/1:9501/1:9505 */
    background: #000; /* one-off literal: hairline renders black in the 1:9499 screenshot, not a token */
  }

  h1 {
    margin: 0;
    font-family: var(--font-display);
    font-size: calc(81.3 * var(--fig)); /* 81.3px, nodes 1:9505/1:9506/1:9507 — proportional-exact per user directive 2026-07-06, supersedes the var(--text-hero-h1) home-normalized token. Safe unqualified: the <1024 block below already overrides font-size with the fluid clamp. */
    line-height: 1.077; /* baseline delta ~87.57px / 81.3px = 1.077, confirms plan's ~1.08 estimate. Unitless ratio — stays as a literal number per the proportional-exact directive (no --fig involved); resolved here instead of via var(--text-hero-h1-lh), which currently points at the HOME hero's own 1.173 ratio, not About's. */
    color: var(--color-ink-alt); /* #1e1e3c exact match */
  }
  h1 .line {
    display: block;
  }
  h1 .accent {
    color: var(--color-orange); /* #f37d2c exact match, node 1:9506 */
  }

  .lede {
    /* Lede (1:9508) is an outlined/vectorized paragraph, not real text, so its
       font-size is reverse-engineered from glyph ink bounds against the
       self-hosted Sora font's own metrics (src/assets/fonts/Sora-VariableFont_wght.ttf,
       unitsPerEm 1000): the "M" in "MC²+" (vector 1:9509) measures 22.63px tall
       against Sora's capHeight/upm of 0.73 → 22.63/0.73 ≈ 31.0px; the "C"
       (1:9510, 23.76px tall) against Sora's C-glyph h/upm of 0.768 → ≈30.9px;
       and the ascender "t" (1:9538, 21.77px tall) against Sora's t h/upm of
       0.702 → ≈31.0px. All three independently converge on ~31px, which
       CORRECTS the plan's rough ~20px guess (Figma wins). Line-height is
       likewise derived from baseline-to-baseline deltas across the 3 lines
       (~40.55px avg) / 31px ≈ 1.31, correcting the plan's assumed 1.4.
       Max-width 49.65rem = 794.44px, the group's own bounding width. */
    max-width: calc(794.44 * var(--fig)); /* 49.65rem = 794.44px, the group's own bounding width — proportional-exact per user directive 2026-07-06. Safe unqualified: the <1024 block below already overrides max-width with 90%. */
    margin: 1.5rem auto 0;
    font-family: var(--font-sans);
    font-size: var(--text-hero-lede); /* left as the home-normalized token here — no existing <1024 override covers font-size, so the proportional-exact calc(31 * var(--fig)) lives in the >=1024 block below instead (mobile must stay untouched) */
    line-height: 1.31; /* derived — see comment above. Unitless ratio — stays as a literal number per the proportional-exact directive; resolved here instead of via var(--text-hero-lede-lh), which currently points at the HOME hero's own 1.4 ratio, not About's. */
    color: var(--color-ink);
  }

  @media (min-width: 1024px) {
    /* Gated here (rather than left unqualified) because none of these
       properties have an existing <1024 override to fall back on below the
       breakpoint — leaving them unqualified would make mobile start scaling
       with viewport width too, which the task requires to stay untouched.

       Placed AFTER `.eyebrow`/`.underline`/`.lede`'s own base rules above
       (final-review fix — see about-fix-report.md §4a): an earlier revision
       of this file placed this exact block BEFORE those three selectors'
       base rules (up near `.hero`), which made it dead code at every
       viewport — at equal specificity, the LATER declaration in source
       order always wins regardless of which media query matches, so the
       unconditional base rules above always won, even at 1920 (confirmed
       via getComputedStyle before this fix). `.orbit`'s own >=1024px
       override above already followed the correct pattern — a separate
       block placed AFTER its base rule — and is the precedent this block
       now matches. */
    .eyebrow {
      font-size: calc(27.07 * var(--fig)); /* 27.07px, node 1:9501 — proportional-exact per user directive 2026-07-06, supersedes the var(--text-hero-eyebrow) home-normalized token */
    }

    .underline {
      width: calc(188.25 * var(--fig)); /* 188.25px, node 1:9500 — proportional-exact per user directive 2026-07-06 */
      margin: calc(45.11 * var(--fig)) auto calc(26.15 * var(--fig)); /* ~45.11px / ~26.15px gaps, nodes 1:9500/1:9501/1:9505 — proportional-exact per user directive 2026-07-06 */
    }

    .lede {
      font-size: calc(31 * var(--fig)); /* 31px, derived — see comment above — proportional-exact per user directive 2026-07-06, supersedes the var(--text-hero-lede) home-normalized token */
    }
  }

  .scroll {
    display: block;
    margin: 3rem auto 0;
  }

  @media (max-width: 1023.98px) {
    h1 {
      font-size: var(--text-hero-h1-fluid); /* was clamp(2.4rem, 7vw, 5.08rem) — normalized to home hero scale per user directive 2026-07-06 */
    }
    .lede {
      max-width: 90%;
    }
  }
</style>
